diff:1619927788:1619927788:=1,76d0%0a%3c (:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Linguistic discrimination in Shanghai towards immigrants from other parts of the country%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: yuluz%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c In Shanghai, local people distinguish immigrants based on their accents and sometimes would treat immigrants differently than local Shanghainese.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Shanghainese, or known as Shanghai dialect, is a variety of the Wu Chinese spoken in the central districts of the city of Shanghai and its surrounding areas. It is the lingua franca of the entire Yangtze River Delta Region, one of the richest regions in China. %0a%3c %0a%3c Shanghainese is richer in vowels and consonants than Mandarin and has voiced initial stops or affricates. Another distinguishing feature of the dialect is its non-differentiation of [n] and [ŋ] when the sound appears in a coda.%0a%3c %0a%3c As the most economically developed metropolitan area in China, Shanghai attracts countless number of immigrants from around the country every year in seek of better job prospects and better lives. However, for some local Shanghainese people, they perceive immigrants as taking away their homeland and taking advantage of their resources. As a result, a lot of them have a somewhat hostile attitude towards immigrants and give them worse treatments than locals. One major way they identify immigrants is by their accents. Due to Shanghainese' unique language features as illustrated in the previous paragraph, it is easy to identify people who don't understand their dialect or don't speak Mandarin with Shanghai accent. %0a%3c %0a%3c For those who they identify as local Shanghainese or more broadly people from the Yangtze River Delta Region, the locals would greet them with a warmer attitude and show them more patience in customer services. For example, one of my friend recounts that when he spoke Mandarin at a quarantine hotel in Shanghai, the receptionist was slow to respond to his request, but as soon as he switched to speaking Shanghainese, the person changed his attitude and took care of his needs immediately. In contrast, another friend of mine was discriminated in Shanghai's job market due to her Northeastern accent and has to turn to other cities for job opportunities.%0a%3c %0a%3c To learn more about the issue, you could refer to the following links:%0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shanghainese#Immigrants%25E2%2580%2599_Opinions_toward_Shanghainese%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: C:)%0a%3c (:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
